                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2 "> Energy is regarded as a propelling force behind economic
                    activities, and private domestic
                    investment is viewed as an economic tool for maintaining and expanding capital stock and
                    production capacity of an economy. Most existing studies on energy, private domestic
                    investment and economic growth relationships mainly concentrated on energy consumption
                    and not energy generation. Besides, their findings were inconclusive. Therefore, this study
                    examined the relationship between energy generation, private domestic investment and
                    economic growth in Nigeria. The study relied on time series data sourced from the Central
                    Bank of Nigeria (CBN) Statistical Bulletin, National Bureau of Statistics (NBS), World Bank
                    and International Energy Agency (IEA) from the period of 1981 – 2016. The data were real
                    GDP as a proxy for economic growth, electricity energy generation, private domestic
                    investment, labour force and implicit price deflator. The study employed Auto regression
                    distributed lag (ARDL) bound test which was found to be the most appropriate to establish
                    the short-run and long-run relationship since there was a fractionally integrated variables.
                    That is, variables at different level of integration (but not at I (2) level). The study revealed
                    that economic growth and private domestic investment have a stable short run and long
                    run relationship impacts. Therefore the null hypothesis of no significant impact relationship
                    between economic growth and private domestic investment was rejected at 5% significance
                    level. Energy generation negatively affected economic growth and private domestic
                    investment both in the long and short run periods. This implies that the potential of private
                    domestic investment to enhance economic growth is significantly possible in the long-run in
                    the Nigerian economy. The consequence of energy generation effects on economic growth
                    and private domestic investment was negative; thus, it served as a disincentive to low
                    productivity and low economic activity and growth.</article>
