                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> Despite the series of efforts put in place by the government to
                    improve the health status of the
                    citizenry in developing countries most especially in Nigeria, low level of economic growth still
                    persists as a result of low ebb of current status and absence of qualitative institutions in the
                    country. Earlier studies in Nigeria focused on the impact of health status on output growth
                    performance without considering the impact of institutional quality simultaneously in the
                    literature. Therefore, the crux of this paper is to empirically investigate the impact of
                    institutional quality and health status on the Nigerian economy, covering the annual time series
                    data period 1980 to 2017 and as well using the Structural Vector Auto-regression (SVAR)
                    technique. The accumulated and impulse response functions, together with forecast error
                    variance decomposition were used to analyze the influence of independent variables to
                    dependent variable. The evidence is in the affirmative from the finding of the study that
                    institutional quality and health status (life expectancy) are very important in the country’s
                    growth experience significantly. Based on the findings of this study, it is therefore
                    recommended that the quality of institutions and improved life expectancy are indispensable as
                    a means of improving and sustaining growth in the country. Hence, the Nigerian government
                    and policy makers should take cognizance of these variables during policy formulations.</article>
