            <details>
                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> This paper examined problems and prospect of roadside trading
                    and hawking in Akure
                    metropolis (i.e. Arakale, Oba Adesida, Ijomu and Obanla road). The specific objectives of the
                    study are to investigate Socio-economic impact of roadside trading and hawking as well as the
                    effects on both traffic flow and pedestrians in the study area. A total of 150 copies of
                    questionnaires were administered on roadside traders and hawkers in the study area.
                    Descriptive analysis method was used for the study such as table, graph and chart. From the
                    analysis, roadside trading as well as hawking were discovered to be the major factors of traffic
                    congestion as well as slow movement of vehicles and pedestrians in the area under study. The
                    reason being that, traders usually display their wares along the roadside which inhibits easy
                    flow of traffic as well as movements of pedestrians along the major corridor of traffic flow. Also,
                    inability of traders to afford the payment of the available stores and lock-up shops in the area
                    allows traders or hawkers to display their goods along the roadside. However, hawkers and
                    other street traders do not pay for over-heads cost such as rents and utility bills. Therefore, the
                    research recommended that government should assist in providing more lock-up and open
                    shops for traders at affordable low rate. In the same vein, there should be restriction in on road
                    side trading as well as hawking along the main road to avoid traffic hold up in the study area.
                </article>
