            <details>
                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> Borrowing is necessary to meet shortfall in internal resources
                    and stimulate the economy.
                    Borrowing is not a problem but the use to which the fund is deployed. Over the years,
                    Nigeria has borrowed large amounts, often at highly concessional interest rates with the
                    hope of putting them on a faster route to development through higher investment, faster
                    growth and poverty reduction. But on the contrary, economic growth and poverty situations
                    are staggering at the back door amidst excess debt. It is obvious that the Nigerian
                    indebtedness may have gone beyond the optimal level that would grow the economy. This
                    paper therefore examines the effect of public debt on economic growth in Nigeria for the
                    periods of 1981 to 2017, with a view to estimating the optimal size of public debt for
                    Nigeria. The paper employs the Ordinary Least Squares method and finds that public debt
                    has a positive effect on economic growth. The paper also finds that the threshold of public
                    debt for Nigeria is around 87%. The paper concludes that public debt has significant effect
                    on economic growth in Nigeria and therefore recommends that government should ensure
                    an optimal utilization of public debt and ensure that public debt is well kept below the
                    estimated threshold of 87% for Nigeria.</article>
            </details>
